<node ID="ID_1170476790" CREATED="1553759866857" MODIFIED="1553759866857"><richcontent TYPE="NODE">

<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p name="1e28" id="1e28" class="graf graf--p graf-after--figure" style="margin-top: 38px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px; font-family: medium-content-serif-font, Georgia, Cambria, Times New Roman, Times, serif; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-size: 21px; line-height: 1.58; letter-spacing: -0.003em; color: black; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255)">
      While researching for this article, I couldn&#8217;t help but think about how archaic the idea of centralised energy distribution is. Large power plants providing electricity to the masses via a centralised grid seems impractical, slow, and expensive, particularly when considering the huge number of people who rely on it.
    </p>
  </body>
</html>
</richcontent>
</node>
<node ID="ID_754542963" CREATED="1553759866926" MODIFIED="1553796461574" LINK="https://www.onaverage.co.uk/consumption-averages/average-electricity-usage"><richcontent TYPE="NODE">

<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p name="079f" id="079f" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p" style="margin-top: 29px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px; font-family: medium-content-serif-font, Georgia, Cambria, Times New Roman, Times, serif; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-size: 21px; line-height: 1.58; letter-spacing: -0.003em; color: black; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255)">
      I endured many school trips to our natural gas power plants in Oxfordshire, England in which we were encouraged to start thinking about energy production and, thankfully, renewable alternatives. Despite many brainstorming sessions, I couldn&#8217;t quite comprehend the sheer scale of what I was witnessing. The plants themselves were hard to ignore in the midst of the countryside, not to mention the gargantuan amount of energy they should produce to maintain every household, which is approximately 4.648 per kWh in the UK and 10,766 kWh in the US annually.
    </p>
  </body>
</html>
</richcontent>
</node>
<node ID="ID_759645417" CREATED="1553759866989" MODIFIED="1553759866989"><richcontent TYPE="NODE">

<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p name="8d10" id="8d10" class="graf graf--p graf-after--p" style="margin-top: 29px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px; font-family: medium-content-serif-font, Georgia, Cambria, Times New Roman, Times, serif; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-size: 21px; line-height: 1.58; letter-spacing: -0.003em; color: black; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255)">
      As technology progresses, such old-fashioned approaches need to be rethought. Bringing blockchain to the energy sector has the potential to transform how people engage with these utilities by bringing control and transparency back to the end users and offering solutions for people who have been neglected by traditional systems.
    </p>
  </body>
</html>
</richcontent>
</node>
